One, two, three.
Testing, testing.

One, two, three.
This is Tuesday, September the 5th.
In the Blocker Building, I have the honor and pleasure of chatting with Dr. Janet McCann,
Professor of English, about her years here at Texas A&M.
And to introduce yourself to someone who might read this transcription
or hear the tape many years in the future,
describe, if you will, your background.
Where did you grow up?
What did parents do?
Where did you go to high school and then college?
Experience before coming to A&M.
Okay.
I grew up in Newark, Delaware.
My mother was a language teacher and my father was a chemist.
I went to the University of Delaware at first,
and then I got thrown out.
I was thrown out of the University of Delaware for producing an illegal newspaper.
After that, I went to Otterbein College, and I graduated from there in 1963.
And then I went on to the University of Pittsburgh for my graduate degree.
I got the master's degree in 1964, and then I was married in 65.
I had, though, by that time, completed my...
coursework.
And so I finished up my doctoral degree at the University of Pittsburgh
to receive it in 1974, ten years later.
But I came out here in 1968.
How did you and A&M become connected?
My husband took a job here in 1968,
and that's when the job market slammed shut.
Before that, there were lots of jobs.
And, in fact, with my master's degree,
in 64, I was offered a whole bunch of jobs.
But then all of a sudden, everything closed down.
And Hugh looked for a job all over,
and finally found a job at Texas A&M.
So he came out here to start teaching in the fall of 1964.
At that time, we had one daughter, Stephanie,
and I was pregnant with the second child.
Did you begin teaching that year?
Yes, I did, but not at first.
I came out in the fall.
Lee Martin was then chair of the English department.
And there was a professor
who apparently had been behaving reprehensibly,
and this person was booted out without ceremony.
And then Lee Martin hired me to take his place
in the middle of the second semester in 1969.
In the spring of 1969, mid-semester, I was hired.
So I took over class.
I took two classes, one Shakespeare class
and two argumentation classes,
and I was hired as an instructor then.
This is the only time I will ask you about salary.
What was the beginning salary in 1969?
The beginning salary was $8,000 a year.
However, we didn't get raises,
and I got that $8,000 a year for many years after that.
So there really wasn't a search process
or a search committee or anything?
No, there certainly wasn't.
In fact, I had sent in when I came out here and looked around.
Actually, I kind of suffered from culture shock
because we'd just come from the University of Chicago,
and this place was very different from the rest of the world then.
For one thing, in the rest of the world,
not everybody had pickups with gun racks in them.
This was something that struck my eye when I got off the bus
because I came out on a bus.
For another, they then had in the Eagle,
which was then the Bryan Eagle,
they had a weekend.
Every weekend, they had a violent death toll,
which included stabbings and shootings and drownings
as well as car crashes.
So I came here, and I thought I was on Mars.
I didn't like the activities for women
because we were kind of supposed to be faculty wives,
and this is not what I thought I'd trained for.
And so I was bored, and I sent a resume
with my newly minted master's on it
to the head of the English department.
Of course, I didn't get any response.
And I was complaining to Manuel Davenport
at a rather well-oiled party
about how crummy things were and how I wanted something to do,
and he said, go in and introduce yourself to the department chair.
And so I did this.
I was very uneasy about this kind of thing,
but I went in and I said, hello, I'm Janet McKenna.
I'd like a job.
He said, well, I'll see what I can do for you next year.
And this was...
This was in the beginning.
The beginning of this spring.
And who was the department?
Lee Martin.
This was Lee, your company.
Oh, and he said, see what he could do for me in the fall.
He said he might have a class or two that nobody wanted.
Well, about a month later, he called me up and said,
can you start teaching Monday?
So that was my beginning.
And this was to replace the faculty member?
Who had been given the royal title, yes.
Would it be appropriate on this to discuss
his alleged shortcomings?
Probably not.
They were fairly spectacular.
Okay, so I was hired to fill in for someone
who had been fired, and I was not told
any of the background of the situation.
And this was about what point in the semester?
This was in the middle of the semester.
So I had a bunch of students.
I got a grade book with a bunch of grades.
And these students seemed extremely disorderly and rude.
And I had not got the impression that Aggie Smith
was like that.
But due to apparently the strained relationships
with the previous instructor, about which I was told nothing,
I had a bunch of loony students all semester.
They said and did strange things in class.
They showed up when they felt like it
and left when they felt like it.
I was going to not teach here anymore.
I was going to look for something somewhere else.
But somebody confided in me that the previous instructor
had set up bad relationships with the students
and therefore I should give it another chance
and take another semester if offered.
So I did.
And of course they were completely different the second time.
All right, now those first classes you taught
were what level courses?
I had a Shakespeare course, which was interesting,
upper level Shakespeare course.
Well, it's not upper level really, it's 212.
Back then there were very few courses.
And this is one thing that makes it very different from now.
There was no real hierarchy within the department.
That is, everybody taught the same thing.
There was not a lot of fighting for classes.
There were very few graduate classes,
and the graduate program was new.
The graduate classes were taught by the same people every time,
so there was no fighting for those.
And otherwise everybody taught the same survey classes,
world lit, American lit, British lit.
There was Shakespeare.
I think there was Chaucer.
I didn't ever teach that.
There were classes in argumentation and freshman composition.
But we all took our turn teaching them,
and I believe it was the head's position
that everybody should have a class of freshman English a year,
so we all did.
And the department was located?
The department was in the academic building.
Can you describe it physically,
about how many people and who were the key,
who were the senior folks?
Okay, the senior, there was John Paul Abbott and Carol Laverty.
There was Harrison Hurst.
There were Sid Cox and, oh gosh, scheduling fellow,
Curtis Shoddy, who's still around.
Frank Pierce was there.
And I'm trying to think of others.
There was somebody named John Gwynn.
There was E.E.
Stokes.
There was a woman, one woman named Muriel Savelle,
and she was only there briefly,
and she was the only woman who was a regular faculty member.
So one full-time female.
One full-time female if you don't count students.
There were a couple of students who were teaching,
a couple of women students who were teaching full-time,
but they were students.
And I'm trying to think of a workload then
for a full-time faculty member in English
with how many sections per semester.
That's hard to answer because I always had nine hours.
But one of the classes was always large,
and they would count that as two classes.
So it was a theoretical 12-hour load,
and some people did have 12-hour loads.
If you taught speech, for instance,
you always had a 12-hour load.
But since they would count a class of 100,
which I frequently had,
it was a nine-hour load.
Now the introductory survey courses
had about how many students,
the freshman English courses?
Oh, the freshman English courses.
They had, as now, a limit of 25,
but they were often smaller.
Often you'd have 17 or 18 students in there.
Now, of course, they're always jammed.
As you were being introduced into the department,
describe how the department
received you.
How did they accept you or not accept you?
They didn't quite know what to do with me.
I was an instructor with a master's degree.
Ph.D.s were not required
for tenure-track work then.
And in fact, some of the people,
Steve Jernigan was there too.
And Steve and Sid and several others,
Frank for that matter,
did not have Ph.D.s.
So that wasn't a problem.
I was the youngest person in the department.
That was kind of a problem.
I kind of fell between the graduate,
in their minds,
I kind of fell between the graduate students
and the professors.
The graduate students were a very motley bunch then.
I was not,
I think I was just kind of
accepted by the younger people in the faculty
who were still considerably older than I,
and overlooked entirely by the older people.
Some of them, Carol Laverty, for instance,
persisted on thinking,
in thinking I was a graduate student.
And then the other people
in the building
didn't consider me,
that is people outside the English department.
I was constantly challenged on my right
to use the elevator.
People would say,
what department are you in?
And sometimes I got a little bit
irritated with this.
And the graduate program
was a master's degree only at that point?
No, it wasn't.
It was a Ph.D. program.
But Ph.D. was already authorized.
Yes, and I think that they graduated
the first one about the year before I came
or the year I came.
In terms of scholarship
and reputation, who were the people best known in the department?
Well, no one had published anything.
I mean, Frank Pierce wrote mystery stories.
He was one of the best published.
Hurth and two of the others,
I think Laverty and somebody else,
had written a textbook.
That was used in the basic literature class,
the 203.
And Lee Martin had written a textbook
called The 500 Word Theme,
which Harry Kreuter then revised.
And that was about it.
Scholarship wasn't the done thing.
Did you find anyone
that you could turn to for advice
in the department?
Who became a friend?
Stanley Archer.
Describe him.
Stanley Archer was always very reserved,
but extremely helpful.
And I always, in fact, until he died,
I always went to Stanley Archer
when I had some kind of naughty question.
Can you give me an example
of any of his advice, his counsel?
Well, several times I had felt
that I had been not treated right
by the department or the university.
And I went to Stanley Archer
before doing anything about it.
And Stanley Archer agreed
that I had been not treated right.
And he looked over letters that I wrote
concerning this that went to various people
and made suggestions on the letters
that were very useful.
Now, describe the students,
your first years here.
Okay.
Leaving aside the bunch of loons
I had the first semester,
they were, for the most part, male.
In fact, in my first class,
these are the ones I took over.
I had only two women in the three classes.
For the next four or five years,
I had by far, I would say,
oh, maybe three to one at least,
men versus women.
They were all, for the most part,
they were all white.
They were all, the uniforms were
by far a greater presence.
You looked out in the class
and you saw mostly uniforms.
They were very, they called me ma'am.
They were very obedient,
again, leaving out this first lot.
However, they had no intellectual,
many of them had no intellectual curiosity.
And English was something they had to get through
on their way to something else.
Sometimes they would develop,
I always liked teaching Shakespeare,
although I have no training in it
because they had a tendency
to bond with Shakespeare
and to actually take an interest
in what they were doing.
But, as far as learning methods
and materials of research,
they were not into this.
The activities with those first students,
can you share any anecdotes
of what it was like with their excuses?
Are there, did any of them ever try to put one over on you?
Oh, many times.
Share some of those.
Okay, one, I had a,
this was a member of the Corps of Cadets,
and he was,
he was missing
for about two-thirds of the semester.
And then he reappeared with this letter,
a sign, Dr. Anderson,
urologist, with a complicated
and detailed description
of what was supposedly wrong
with this young man's urinary system
that had caused him to miss my class.
And it was supposedly signed by his father, too,
and by the,
by Dr. Anderson.
And I read the thing
and it sounded a little funny.
The doctor would be quite so free with details.
In fact, it sounded a little bit like
it had been even taken from somewhere.
So I didn't,
he was supposed to come around Monday.
I was supposed to,
I went to a party on Friday evening,
and there was Dr. Anderson.
So I asked him about this letter,
and he said that the student had been to his office
for some sort of minor problem
at the beginning of the semester,
but he had never written any letter for him.
This guy had pinched the,
the stationery.
And so I,
he showed up on Monday,
and I said,
Mr. Smith, that's a pseudonym,
would you like to hear
what Dr. Anderson said about your letter?
And he said,
no ma'am, I don't think I would,
and I never saw him again.
My favorite is a youngster who told me
the first day of the semester
that his grandfather was very ill.
I expressed my concern,
my sadness, I hope it's not serious,
oh, very serious,
oh, gee, gee.
He said, in fact,
he may not survive this semester.
I said, well, I'll work with you,
and we'll do the best we can.
As he walked out the door,
he turned over his shoulder,
and he said, in fact,
it's almost certain he's going to die
the first day of deer season.
And he grinned as he walked away.
What about classroom behavior patterns?
How did, how did Aggies behave in class
in those early years?
Politely, for the most part.
They, they tended to calculate
what they needed to do
to get through the course,
and do that much,
and they were always polite.
Back then, there was such a thing
as a gentleman's C
that many of them were quite content to receive.
I never had any trouble with students
in those first years at all,
except for, again,
leaving aside this first lot.
And a large core percentage in those years.
Yes, uh-huh.
And in general,
were these country boys or city?
They were country boys for the most part.
And very few liberal arts majors.
Yes, few liberal arts majors.
And the, the,
those who were,
I tended not to get
because I tended to teach basic classes.
On the other hand,
there weren't that many
specialized classes.
For instance,
I'm in creative writing,
and that's what I do now.
I coordinate the creative writing classes.
There was no creative writing.
Then after years and years,
Frank Pierce, I think,
started creative writing,
and Dick Costa taught creative writing.
And there was one class a year.
And you were lucky to get your ten students
that you needed
to have that class make.
Now, of course,
we have, we can't offer enough.
We, we,
especially our 200-level courses,
we always get,
we're offering four sections this time,
and I had dozens and dozens of requests
to be forced in,
but you can't.
It's, it's 225 students
to teach creative writing.
That's enough students.
You can't do any more than that.
Teach them.
Describe registration in that era,
those early years.
Wow.
As I recall,
there were long tables.
There were, there was a room somewhere,
maybe in Heaton,
I don't remember where it was.
All right.
Now,
Sabisa and G. Raleigh,
or had we already moved out of that,
where you, where faculty used to go
on registration day,
the students went through there?
I don't remember where the,
where the, I just remember sitting at these tables
and having people come in.
I would be representing like Shakespeare,
and people would sign up.
I don't remember when that stopped,
and I don't remember where it was,
but I certainly remember doing it.
In those, in those early years,
did you have any normal rules,
or in your syllabus,
did you have any guidelines
that you gave to the students
of what you expected?
No.
Some people did.
I mean, I had a syllabus,
if you mean assignments,
and so forth.
Yes, I had a syllabus
with the assignments on it,
and the textbook,
and usually it was one page,
and that was it.
And, and,
and, and,
and, and,
and, and,
did you check achieve in those years?
Everyday?
No.
I didn't.
Basically,
though, after the first two weeks at least,
I knew who everybody was
in the smaller classes.
In the bigger classes,
I always left it up to them
if they wanted to come to class,
and I think this is one of the reasons
that I never had any trouble with students
during those, during that time period
because I didn't make them come to class.
If they missed a quiz,
they could not make it up.
The assignment dates, though, including the quizzes, were on the sheet, so anyone who
could do satisfactory work without attending the lectures, maybe by reading the textbook
and the other materials, that was all right with me.
All right.
And you were a pioneer female faculty member.
Did women students turn to you occasionally for any advice or counsel?
Actually, the students who came to me for advice and counsel back then were mostly
men, young men.
I think they saw me as mama.
As far as the young women were concerned, I don't know where they went, but they didn't
come to me.
And what was the normal title that the students gave you when they spoke to you?
They tended to call me Mrs. McCann.
Of course, I did not have a Ph.D. then.
So I wouldn't...
I would not have been Dr. McCann.
But they tended to call me Mrs. McCann.
And they were polite.
And they were polite.
Mrs. McCann, ma'am.
All right.
Let's back up a little and describe how it was to get settled into this community.
You all found a place to live and children and so forth.
Yes.
Now, Hugh came out a couple of weeks after he was hired, he came out and stayed with
Manuel Davenport for three or four days.
And bought a house.
And the house cost $19,000.
It was on Carter Creek Parkway.
And it was a nice little brick house, it had three bedrooms in a very pleasant area.
Uh, so we didn't have any trouble with that.
And the children were not yet school age or were they...
No, they were not.
And we took them to French's Royal Tat.
Mm hmm.
which actually worked out very well for my daughter.
I think it was not the right place for my son,
but I didn't know that then.
It seemed fine.
Do you remember what that daycare cost then?
Yeah, it cost $65 a month for one,
and I think $95, yeah.
I reduced right over to it.
And your neighbors, how were they
in being receptive to a newcomer?
Well, I didn't like the neighbors, frankly.
I thought them bigots.
For one thing, we had a maid, as everybody did then,
and they were very upset because I
let the maid bring her little girl
to play with my little girl, and this
caused all kinds of problems.
So I didn't get on very well with the neighbors.
I did also, before I worked in the fall,
I did go to some of their little cafes.
They had coffee clutches, and I hated them.
That is, not the neighbors, but those morning coffees
where people would discuss their families and their lives.
And to me, it seemed extremely limited and sterile.
And this led to my being very anxious to get out of there
and talk to Emanuel Davenport about the possibility
of escape.
But no, the neighbors were not neighbors I would have chosen.
They were not affiliated with the neighbors.
The neighbors I liked, too, were the three of them.
With the university, they worked in a factory,
and now I can't think where, or which.
Was it a shoe factory?
It could have been a shoe factory.
I don't remember, but I do remember
that neighbors on both sides worked in a factory
and were friends.
And the neighbor behind us, I liked
him somewhat better, that he was military.
Across the street from us was Dr. Capeerton, the skin person.
And they were at all different places.
They effected me.
They held themselves aloof, the capertins.
They had a bigger house,
and they kind of didn't socialize too much with the rest of us.
In fact, there was a whole little enclave of bigger houses across the street.
But once I got out of the neighborhood, it was pleasant enough.
I mean, it was certainly a nice place to live.
The neighbors were decent people.
They were just very narrow-minded.
What about shopping?
There was nothing much.
There was the Townsend Shopping Center, and that was it.
There was, I believe, a Sears there.
There was a pharmacy with a little diner in it,
where they used to have pharmacies.
And we only had one car.
So actually, the semester I spent home alone was not fun
because I didn't have the car either, and I had the little girl.
But what I would do would be to wheel her
to the pharmacy, and I would wheel her to the pharmacy.
And then we would go to the Townshire Shopping Center.
And there we would have, like, ice cream sundaes
at the little diner inside it, and go to Sears maybe.
But there was not much.
There was a Kroger's that was.
Now we're Hastings, you know, Manner East.
And there was the Townshire Shopping Center.
And there was downtown College Station.
And one thing, I mean, downtown Bryan, I'm sorry.
There was nothing downtown College Station
except for a couple of shoe places and barbershops
and all the student bars.
One thing I noticed, though, was that back then,
when you came into town, all the local merchants
gave you these credit cards.
They called you up, and they gave you credit cards
that were good for their own stores, Beverly, Braley.
I understand something terrible happened to him.
He just retired.
And he was killed in an accident.
It probably wasn't an accident.
Yeah, don't put that in the...
I forgot about the machine.
Let's see.
Did you become involved in any community activities?
Not right away.
After I started working, I did.
Because I must say that I had a lot more leisure
as an instructor and then later as a lecturer even
than I have now.
Now, any spare time is immediately filled in.
Back then, I just taught my classes and went home,
so I was a Girl Scout leader.
I worked at the Bryan City Mission.
I worked for the Brazos Valley Literacy Council.
I did all these things.
Church, synagogue, did you attend?
Oh, yeah, we're Catholic.
We went to church.
Which, describe the parish y'all attended.
Back then, we attended, let's see.
We attended St. Mary's.
And it was not that different from the way it is now.
I mean, it was full of Aggies.
Yeah, that was it.
St. Mary's was our parish for years and years.
And then once they built St. Thomas,
we sort of moved over there.
But what frequently happens is that my husband
goes to St. Thomas Aquinas and I still go to St. Mary's
because, A, I don't like to get up to go to the 830 Mass,
and, B, I like going to St. Mary's.
This man, Manuel Davenport.
Since I won't be able to interview him,
tell me as much as you can.
How did y'all come to know him in the first place?
And then describe him as much as you can
because we need to be sure to include him in this reservoir.
Yeah.
He, first of all, invited you to stay with him
and look for a house and then helped you find a house.
But how did they even...
He hired you.
Oh.
There was a search and he hired you.
Oh, in philosophy?
Yeah.
Oh, I'm sorry.
Yeah, no, no problem.
But there was a search in philosophy and they hired you.
And then they invited him to come out and stay with them
and find accommodations.
So he did that.
And I was, at this time, pregnant.
And I told him that I wanted a house.
I said I wanted to start with a house.
So, although we didn't have very much money,
with my parents' help, it was possible to buy this house.
And back then, too, it was much easier to get a bank loan.
There wasn't much.
There wasn't much of a check.
You know, you were an A&M professor.
You could have the loan.
So we got this house on Carter Creek Parkway.
But the Davenports were very nice to Hugh.
And I can't imagine that happening now,
that you hire somebody and the head invites this person
to stay with them for three or four days
and helps them find a house.
So then we came out.
And I liked the philosophy department immediately.
It was about how many?
I would say...
I would say about six.
There was Ed Harris and Davenport and Stadelman and Becca.
Who am I missing?
I don't think there was anybody else besides Hugh.
Those are the people I remember from parties.
That is, as permanent members.
